<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41119210</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>21</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1175-5334</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>5631</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>02</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Zootaxa</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Zootaxa</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Two new nematode species of the family Sphaerolaimidae (Nematoda, Monhysterida) from the Yellow Sea, China.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>335</StartPage><EndPage>348</EndPage><MedlinePgn>335-348</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.11646/zootaxa.5631.2.6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Two new species of free-living marine nematodes from the subtidal zone of the Yellow Sea were found and are described. Sphaerolaimus articulatus sp. nov. is characterized by circular amphidial fovea located at the level of the gymnostoma, the longest subcephalic setae 1520 m long, spicules arcuate, divided into two parts by a fine suture anterior to the middle, handle-shaped proximally and blunt distally and gubernaculum with two dorsally hook-shaped apophyses. The second new species, Parasphaerolaimus sinensis sp. nov. is characterized by amphidial fovea located at the level of the gymnostoma base, length of longest subcephalic setae 1922 m in males, 67 m in females, cuticle with lateral longitudinal alae, 15 m in males, 8 m in females, slender and slightly curved spicules 1.31.8 cloacal body diameter, gubernaculum with dorsally straight apophyses, 911 m long, position of the vulva very close to the anus, 8487% of body length from anterior end and ovoviviparity.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Zhai</LastName><ForeName>Hongxiu</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Agriculture and Biology; Liaocheng University; Liaocheng 252059; China. zhaihongxiu@lcu.edu.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Liu</LastName><ForeName>Lin</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Agriculture and Biology; Liaocheng University; Liaocheng 252059; China. linliu906@163.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Huang</LastName><ForeName>Mian</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Agriculture and Biology; Liaocheng University; Liaocheng 252059; China. huangmian@lcu.edu.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>02</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>New Zealand</Country><MedlineTA>Zootaxa</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101179386</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1175-5326</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000818" MajorTopicYN="N">Animals</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D008297" MajorTopicYN="N">Male</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005260" MajorTopicYN="N">Female</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D002681" MajorTopicYN="N" Type="Geographic">China</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D049628" MajorTopicYN="N">Body Size</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D063147" MajorTopicYN="N">Animal Distribution</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000825" MajorTopicYN="N">Animal Structures</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000033" MajorTopicYN="N">anatomy &amp; hist